<HEAD>National Guard Joins Fight Against Forest Fires</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT that governor authorized use of, sted sent
in, military reinforcements; SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that 3,000, sted
15,000, people are involved in fighting 15,000 acres of fires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> declared a state of extreme emergency Friday, putting military reinforcements on call to help the battle against hundreds of forest fires burning out of control. The emergency proclamation, which allows the state to use the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, will last for 30 days or until the fire danger subsides. The <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> estimated about 3,000 people were working as firefighters or support personnel to battle 15,000 acres of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> fires. The weather cooperated in northern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> with high humidity that slowed the flames, while the opposite was true for the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. `` The humidity dropped considerably,'' said <PERSON> Lynette </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> forest spokeswoman. `` When the air dried out, the fires got up and ran.'' A lightning storm earlier this week covered central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> with 500 fires, some limited to just a burning tree. Firefighters concentrated on the larger blazes, while parachuting smokejumpers or helicopter-borne crews tackled the small ones. The containment of small fires and shuffling of crews Friday left it difficult to assess total acreage burned or manpower on the fire lines. The top-priority fire in the state was the 1,500-acre <LOCATION> Fleming </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> blaze near Banks, north of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, fire information officer for the <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> forest north of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>. It burned on state and <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> forest land. The second fire of concern was the 600-acre Dollar Creek fire near the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> the </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salmon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> east of <ORGANIZATION> Cascade </ORGANIZATION> because of the chance its destruction of ground cover could lead to erosion into the river. Fire bosses in the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> focused on the 6,500-acre <LOCATION> Deer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> blaze near <LOCATION> Mann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Weiser </LOCATION>, which had tripled in size since Thursday and was burning in critical sharptail grouse habitat. In the <ORGANIZATION> Payette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, about 500 firefighters from all over the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> had contained 70 of 130 fires and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> erected a temporary tower at the McCall airport to monitor the scores of retardant bombers and smoke jumper planes in the region.
