<HEAD>Man Convicted in Killing of Church Volunteer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man was found guilty of first-degree murder Friday in the killing of a church volunteer, more than two years after he was captured in the longest manhunt in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> history. The jury deliberated for 2 -LCB- hours before returning the verdict against <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 35, in <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The penalty phase of the two-week trial is scheduled to begin at 9:30 a.m. Saturday, and the state is asking for the death penalty. The jury can recommend either death or life imprisonment. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Finnical </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general and the lead prosecutor in the case, said testimony from ballistics experts showed the gun <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> had when he was arrested in <LOCATION> Ada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, was the one that killed caretaker <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> in a Doolittle church on April 1, 1987. `` Circumstantial evidence conclusively _ conclusively _ proves <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> murdered this man,'' <PERSON> Finnical </PERSON> told the jury. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON>, had questioned the validity of the ballistics results. `` What you have here is the state grasping at straws. They have to put someone in the church,'' <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON> said. At the time Long was killed, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was the subject of a massive manhunt after a man matching his description fled from a <LOCATION> Rolla </LOCATION> motel room a few days earlier. A police officer was wounded in that incident.
