<HEAD>Boy Trying to Kill Bugs Sets Home Afire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teen-ager accidentally set fire to his family's home while trying to kill bugs on a porch, officials said. The fire started when the 14-year-old boy lit insect repellent after spraying it on the bugs, said <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Capt. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Epp </PERSON>. The flames ignited bushes, then shot up and covered the front porch and its roof and burned into the wall of a second-floor bedroom. Thursday's fire caused about $ 40,000 damage to the <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> McGehan </PERSON> home, said <PERSON> Epp </PERSON>. No one was injured. A cat, two dogs, a parakeet and a guinea pig were saved from the smoke-filled house, officials said. The boy was not identified.
