<HEAD>FCC `Voodoo Priests' Not Helping Radio</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 2 p.m. EDT. Time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radio is being ill-served by `` voodoo priests'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> who seem to think just about anyone should be able to own a station, a broadcasting lobbyist says. A deregulation-minded <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has been kind to broadcasters in many ways during the 1980s, but has sometimes gone too far in its rush to impose a free-market ethic, said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>. `` If there were a modern-day <PERSON> Rip </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Winkle </PERSON> broadcaster who had gone to sleep in 1980 and reawakened this year, he would scarcely believe the changes,'' <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said in remarks prepared for delivery today at the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. `` The entire communications landscape has changed,'' he said. `` Deregulation has come faster and gone farther than our industry ever asked or dreamed of.'' Under <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> and his predecessor, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, the Fairness Doctrine has been lifted and broadcasters received favorable improvements in the license-renewal process. <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said broadcasters were grateful for those victories, but that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has caused other headaches. Noting that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> loosened rules for acquiring radio station licenses, <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said it appeared the commission had `` become so obsessed with regulation by marketplace economic theory that it seemingly is interested in providing every man, woman and child with their own radio station.'' `` Ole Rip would be surprised that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has no apparent concern for preserving the system of local service by financially healthy stations that has served the American public so well for the past 70 years,'' he said. `` Our awakening broadcaster would think his world was being ruled by voodoo priests. `` As a result of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s Alice-in-Wonderland allocations policies, it is faced with a growing backlog of applications for new facilities and minor station modifications. <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> official acknowledged recently that a new ruling allowing increased power for small FM stations may increase the application backlog from six months to 18 months. And it was particularly galling to broadcasters, he said, that even as the backlog grows, a deficit-conscious <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wants to increase application fees by 13 percent. <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> lashed out at <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> proposals to hold lotteries, auctions and private negotiations to allocate and assign station licenses. `` How can the commission say with a straight face that is can choose broadcast applicants who will best serve the public interest by reading ping-pong balls or conducting lotteries?'' The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said, `` has allowed so many new stations on the AM band that it has created destructive interference and undermined the financial health of many stations to the determinant of local service.''
