<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Japan-Stress     07-29 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Japan-Stress,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>More than 50 Percent Of Japanese Feel Stress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than half of all Japanese suffer from stress caused by work or relationships, but men are more likely to drink and women more likely to shop to deal with it, a government survey said today. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s national survey, conducted June 1988 among Japanese over 12 years of age, almost 52 percent of 36,146 people said they feel stress in their daily lives. More than 70 percent answered they can handle stress, but 10 percent said they were overwhelmed, the ministry report said. While 49.2 percent of 17,692 men said they feel stress, 54.4 percent of 18,454 women said they do. The survey pointed out men and women try to release stress differently. While drinking, exercise, television and radio were major remedies for men, chatting, idle time and shopping were the top three remedies for women.
</TEXT>
