<HEAD>Soviet Spy Ship Turns Fleeing Cubans Over to US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Cubans who survived almost a week at sea were rescued by a Soviet spy ship prowling off <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, which turned them over to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, who had no recollection of any previous rescue by Soviet sailors of fleeing Cubans, were puzzling over why the ship had not turned over the men, found floating 26 miles off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast, to <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> authorities. `` In the time I've been here in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, this is the first time,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said Friday. `` I've had two tours of duty here, so this is something new for us.'' The men were badly sunburned, dehydrated and exhausted after a six-day, 125-mile voyage during which they lost a companion and at one point resorted to catching a bird with bare hands and eating it raw. They were taken to <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Memorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and treated for dehydration and severe sunburn. A hospital spokesman said they were in stable condition Friday night. The Soviet ship, identified in the reference book <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>'s Fighting Ships as the 274-foot <LOCATION> Zaporozhye </LOCATION>, spotted the three clinging to an inner tube and rescued them Friday morning, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said The Soviet captain refused to allow a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> party to board, and the Cubans were transferred by raft to a patrol boat for their trip to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. The refugees identified themselves as <PERSON> Arsenio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, 46, his son <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, 17, and <PERSON> Arsenio </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>, 48. <PERSON> Junior </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlais </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>, 20, cousin and nephew to the others, was lost at sea. The men had secretly built a 12-foot wooden rowboat in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, which they loaded with supplies and tied to a tractor-trailer tire inner tube. The rowboat overturned Monday night in rough seas, spilling their provisions. The men clung to the inner tube. They caught some small fish by hand, <PERSON> Arsenio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said. A seabird landed on his head at one point, he said. He managed to catch it and they ate it. The men lost track of time and were n't sure when <PERSON> Arlais </PERSON> became delirious and thought he saw the lights of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. He let go of the tube and drifted away, they said. Cuban refugees who make it to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> usually are turned over to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and released to relatives after questioning. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has picked up 97 Cubans on rafts this year, 31 this month alone. The Soviet ship has been operating for several months off <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> on intelligence-collecting operations, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> fleet spokesman in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. Coast Guardsman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Slater </PERSON> said the Soviets may not have realized the men were fleeing <LOCATION> C