<HEAD>Roadside Sign Catches Dopey Dopers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLE LAKE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sheriff played some mind games to rope in drug users headed for a country music fest in the north woods, and the trick paid off with 20 arrests. After posting a sign Friday that read `` Narcotics Inspection Ahead,'' six officers in camouflage hid by the roadside, positioning themselves so they could see the reaction of the people in passing vehicles on state Route 55. If the cars slowed down and those inside tried to conceal or discard something, the officers radioed ahead for patrolmen to pull them over, said <LOCATION> Langlade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Steger </PERSON>. Some open beer cans were tossed out windows, but no one threw drugs away, one officer told a reporter at the scene. `` They're too expensive,'' he said. Most of the arrests were for marijuana possession, and a few were for cocaine possession and posession with intent to deliver, he said. Officers accepted $ 100 bail in the form of personal checks, credit cards or cash. Soon after the operation began, promoters of the weekend country music festival at the <LOCATION> Mole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservation </LOCATION>, about 220 miles north of <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, arrived at the arrest site a few miles south of the reservation to find out what was going on. `` It did n't take long for the word to spread,'' <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Steger </PERSON> said accusations of entrapment did not worry him. `` There was good probable cause on all the stops we did make,'' he said.
