<HEAD>Ailing Tanker Limping Toward Dry Dock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Exxon Cleanup, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ailing <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> limped toward safe harbor today, after postponing massive hull repairs for weeks while waiting offshore until environmental questions could be answered. The tanker involved in the nation's worst oil spill was scheduled to enter <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> early Sunday, under tow as it has been throughout the 2,500-mile journey south from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Divers were confident they had cut off all the dangling steel plates torn loose during the southerly voyage and that the gutted tanker would be able to pass through the harbor's shallows. State environment officials said they would keep close watch on the lumbering ship when it enters the bay under escort, surrounded by a flotilla of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> boats. Local <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> activists said they'd be watching too, following at a distance after staging a protest demonstration against <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> planned for Sunday morning. `` We are concerned that it will be discharging into the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nadeau </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. `` If it does have some oil slicks coming out of it, we'll be able to see that.'' <PERSON> Nadeau </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> wants to see the Valdez reach the dock safely because more environmental damage could occur if the tanker remains at sea any longer. An 18-mile oil slick was spotted near the tanker July 10, and since then the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> has been halted about 55 miles off the coast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. Numerous tests were conducted and the emergency plate-cutting work was undertaken. Exxon officials and state negotiators hammered out an agreement to allow <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> into port. The Valdez, which spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil after slamming into a submerged reef in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, was to execute a series of maneuvers, simulating what it will have to do inside the harbor, before being allowed into the bay. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials insist that periodict discharges from the Valdez are nontoxic with barely detectable traces of oil. State officials, leery of Exxon assurances, have said the ship is releasing significant pollutants.
