<HEAD>Eight Die in Latest Violence; Police Say One-Sixth of Population
Has Fled</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MOHAMMED SALAM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> forces kept up their relentless rocket attacks in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today, killing eight people and wounding 42 in a wave of bloodshed that has driven out all but a fraction of the populace, police said. Fires blazed out of control and palls of thick, black smoke billowed from gaping holes that rockets and shells made in apartment buildings in both Moslem and Christian sectors. The new casualties raised the overall toll to 502 killed and 2,056 wounded in the 19-week confrontation between Christian forces and Syrian army gunners. A police spokesman, who can not be named under regulations, estimated that only about 250,000 people remain in the city that was home to an estimated 1.5 million residents when the current fighting broke out March 8. The spokesman said about 50 percent of the population fled in the first three months of the fighting and about 350,000 people have fled in the past 10 days. Most of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s residents have fled to south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, the eastern <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> valley </LOCATION> and the mountain resorts northeast of the city to escape the deadly shelling duels, the spokesman said. Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> radio stations interrupted regular programming early in the day to report that shelling duels were continuing across a mountain range southeast of the capital. `` The fight started very early today,'' the Moslem-run <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> radio reported in a news flash. The Christian-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> urged civilians to `` take maximum precaution because the shelling might escalate and spread to other areas.'' The thuds of exploding shells echoed across the wooded hills south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> early in the day as Syrian army gunners pounded the Christian suburb of <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION> east of the capital. <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION> houses the presidential palace that has been used as the main headquarters for <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> since the confrontation broke out. Several motorists, heading to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to inspect their deserted apartments and businesses, turned back to south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and other safe areas to avoid being caught in the cross-fire. `` They're shelling his palace. He'll respond soon. I do n't want to be around when his response starts,'' said <PERSON> Marwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaar </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem who owns a money exchange company. <PERSON> Shaar </PERSON> spoke in the Syrian-policed <LOCATION> Khaldeh </LOCATION> area, seven miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The area was under fierce shelling from <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners overnight The escalating shelling duels coincided with reports in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s heated rumor mill that either <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> or the Syrians would have to storm their opponent's positions to break out of the 4-month shelling duel that has not altered either side's areas of influence. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, in an interview with the weekly <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> An-Nahar </ORGANIZATION>, pledged that `` We shall be advancing against the occupied areas.'' He did not elaborate. The 54-year-old Maronite general had declared a `` war of liberation'' against <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s 40,000 troops deployed in predominantly Moslem sections of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. He made the move after the Syrians and allied forces besieged his 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in retaliation for his blockade of ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of the capital.
