<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0452,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Troops To Start Withdrawal Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with new casualty figures; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said thousands of Indian troops would begin leaving today, the second anniversary of an accord that brought them to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to quell a rebellion but instead fueled more violence. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> agreed on Friday to resume withdrawing its 45,000 peacekeeping troops, averting a showdown with <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, who had called the continued troop presence a threat to his country's independence. The government said 3,000 to 4,000 troops would begin leaving today. `` The <LOCATION> Indo-Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> problem to a great extent has been resolved,'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said before he and a six-member delegation left for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> to discuss a timetable for the withdrawal of the rest of the Indian troops. `` <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s decision to recommence the withdrawal process has further consolidated the 2,500-year-old friendship between the two countries,'' he said. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> originally sought the departure of all Indian troops by today, but <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> maintained an immediate withdrawal would worsen ethnic violence. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s decision Friday came on one of the most violent days, when 74 people were killed. Casualties included nine Tamil guerrillas killed Friday in two separate clashes with Indian troops, according to military officials who can not be identified under briefing rules. State television said most victims were killed by Sri Lankan forces in the Sinhalese heartland, where extremists have violently protested government peace efforts and where Indian forces are not deployed. The military also announced at least 150 people have died since the government declared a nationwide curfew from midnight Thursday to 6 a.m. Sunday to prevent violence during the anniversary. The two-year <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> military presence has fueled ethnic violence among Tamil guerrillas the Indians were supposed to disarm and Sinhalese extremists who say the Indian presence violates Sri Lankan sovereignty. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, spurred by its own politically powerful Tamil ethnic minority of 60 million, sent troops to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to enforce a July 29, 1987, peace accord sponsored by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and designed to give ethnic Tamils some autonomy in northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. But the biggest Tamil guerrilla group, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, reneged and began attacking the Indians. Tamils, who make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population and control the government and armed forces. Sinhalese extremists upset with the concessions made to Tamils, meanwhile, began attacking moderate Sinhalese who supported the peace overtures. Sinhalese radicals are accused of killing 4,000 people, mostly Sinhalese government officials and supporters, since Indian troops began arriving. Another 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have died in the Tamil separatist war that started in 1983. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said it hopes <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s decision saves lives `` We welcome this development and hope that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> will be successful in reaching an agreement on a timetable for withdrawal that minimizes bloodshed while recognizing <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s sovereignty and independence,'' said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> It remained unclear when all of the Indian troops would leave. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> and six other Sri Lankan officials were to fly to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> on Friday to discuss a timetable for the withdrawal of the rest of the Indian troops. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> earlier said Sri Lankan troops would leave the barracks where they have been confined for two years and resume patrols in Tamil areas. At the peak of its involvement in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s peacekeeping force numbered at least 70,000 The most recent withdrawals were in January and February when about 5,000 soldiers left shortly after <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> took office.
</TEXT>
