<HEAD>Soviet Opposition Faction Takes Form at Moscow Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 250 reform-minded lawmakers held a strategy meeting today for what promises to become the national parliament's first organized opposition in nearly 70 years The fledgling faction of Soviet legislators, operating under the bland title of the `` Inter-Regional Deputies' Group,'' is pushing for more radical economic reform and greater democracy. Progressive economist <PERSON> Gavriil </PERSON> <PERSON> Popov </PERSON> opened the group's first general meeting in the crowded auditorium of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Filmmakers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> with a call to bring reform through careful legal changes instead of the government's `` spontaneous approach'' to crisis after crisis Speakers then began discussing amendments and projects they want to lobby for in the Supreme Soviet legislature. Organizers said many more than the 250 deputies who registered for the two-day general meeting wanted to come, but some could not obtain tickets and others were too involved in local events. All 2,250 deputies elected to this spring's <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies were eligible to join <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, which dubbed the group `` left-radicals,'' said today they have a place in the reform process but that some legislators `` have expressed the fear that in this complex time for the country, when unity of action is required, this ` left-radical group' might turn into some kind of opposition.'' In fact, some members say, the group already sees itself as an opposition faction but avoids saying so publicly. `` We're avoiding the words ` opposition' and ` faction' because they're perceived negatively,'' <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> deputy <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreyev </PERSON> said in an interview. `` But in actuality, this is a group of opposition deputies who want to work in an organized way at the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the Supreme Soviet.'' <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> deputy <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Stankevich </PERSON>, writing in the first issue of the group's newspaper, `` the People's Deputy,'' said that fears instilled by years of political tyranny made people shy away from the idea of open opposition. `` No sooner does someone pronounce the words ` faction' and ` opposition' from the rostrum than some people feel their hearts drop into their feet and their backs break out in sweat, and others get a hunter's spark in their eyes and a militant shout in their throats,'' he wrote. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> predicted that maverick Communist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> would be elected head of the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Elections were to be held on Sunday. Thus far, the group has been tolerated but given no concrete support by the government apparatus and was denied its own meeting place in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, organizers said. It is working on setting up its own staff and support base, said <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotova </PERSON>, head of the two-week-old `` Foundation of Deputies' Initiatives. The foundation is searching for legal ways for voters to contribute money to their deputies and also hopes to act as a data bank and channel for voters' requests, <PERSON> Kotova </PERSON> said. `` Our desired aim is to have the equivalent of a Western party,'' she said. The last alternative party to survive the Bolshevik purges, the Left Socialist Revolutionaries, was suppressed in 1922. The <ORGANIZATION> Inter-Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> grew out of `` the despair of the radically-inclined minority'' during the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> when they found virtually all their motions blocked by what one deputy called the `` aggressively obedient majority,'' the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputy said. <PERSON> Popov </PERSON> proposed creation of an independent group of deputies on May 27, the third day of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> lasted two weeks; it served as a national stage for striking revelations about the country's crises and launched commissions but produced little actual legislation. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` postponed the resolution of essential problems for an undefined period,'' the People's Deputy said, `` and that led to strikes and the sharpening of the inter-ethnic situation.'' Among questions discussed today were amendments that would give enterprises more independence from ministries and a resolution asking that Soviets living abroad who were stripped of their citizenship be allowed to reclaim it.
