<HEAD>Hungary Says It Has Torn Down Half Its Border Fence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has dismantled nearly half of the barbed wire fence and alarm system that has divided this communist nation from the West for more than 30 years, an official said. <PERSON> Balazs </PERSON> <PERSON> Novaki </PERSON>, deputy commander in chief of the Hungarian frontier guards, told reporters on Friday that work on removing <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s `` iron curtain'' has progressed more swiftly than planned. Hungarian leaders presented President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> with a piece of the barbed wire fence when he visited <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> earlier this month. Speaking at a news conference at the border town of <LOCATION> Koeszeg </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Novaki </PERSON> said the system now has been removed from a 75-mile section of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s 160-mile border with neutral <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. During the spring, workers began cutting through the barbed wire at four stops along the border, and officials said then they expected to dismantle the barrier completely by Dec. 1, 1990. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> decided in February to remove the fence and electronic alarm system that was installed in 1972. <PERSON> Novaki </PERSON> said restrictions in the 15-mile-wide border zone, such as on travel and movement, will be lifted Aug. 1 but that guards will continue to patrol the border. The number of Western tourists visiting <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has increased considerably this year, <PERSON> Novaki </PERSON> said, with the biggest increases among visitors from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Officials also have said there has been a substantial increase in the number of citizens from other <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries attempting to flee to the West over the Hungarian border since they began dismantling the fence. Most are from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, officials have said.
