<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan Bjt   07-29 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan, Bjt,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Arrive Before Relief, Threatening Another Year of Starvation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rainy season has hit southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, and a relief operation intended to get food to the region is behind schedule and hindered by soggy roads and fears of rebel attacks. In <LOCATION> Kosti </LOCATION> south of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, 17,500 tons of emergency supplies are just now being loaded on <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barges that were to have gone south weeks ago. Boxcars loaded with 1,350 tons of other supplies are parked in a railroad yard, immovable for fear the train will be attacked by rebels or starving peasants, as previous ones were. While nearly three-fourths of the targeted 105,000 tons reached redistribution points before the rains, which will make them inaccessible, relief workers say pockets of potential starvation remain in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, an area the size of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` One can not speak of a disaster for the moment, but some of these areas will have trouble,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Junod </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. `` The extent depends on the ecological situation and the peace talks.'' Operation Lifeline <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, coordinated by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and using trucks, trains and barges, was to have provided enough supplies to help people displaced by the southern civil war survive the summer monsoon-like rains. Officials report that 72,000 tons have been moved. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> mounted a smaller airborne operation that failed to meet its goal, transporting 6,000 tons of a planned 7,000 to 8,000 tons. `` The situation in the rebel-held territories is a bit tricky,'' <PERSON> Junod </PERSON> said. `` We've not been able to send in enough food because of the onset of the rains.'' Trucks and trains are virtually useless in the rainy season. Neither the railroad bed nor the roads in the south, mostly rutted pathways, are constructed well enough to withstand the downpours. In 1988, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials say 250,000 southerners died of starvation, flood or disease during the rainy season. The estimate of some Western relief workers is twice that. Both <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and other relief officials said Operation Lifeline had to succeed to save 100,000 people from starving to death this summer. Some relief workers in this wretchedly poor country, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest with only a tiny network of roads and railways, blame mismanagement and lack of clear planning for the failure of both the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> efforts to reach their goals, despite the huge expenditures The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> airlift cost $ 35 million from December, when it began, to June. Operation Lifeline <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, which began April 1, was scheduled to cost $ 132 million, which donors pledged at a March conference in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general's special representative for the project, announced in mid-July a need for an additional $ 40 million. With previous increases, that brought the total to $ 200 million. Both sides in the civil war generally have honored a cease-fire since May, but unknown gunmen have attacked relief trucks and trains, with 11 people killed and several boxcars looted. A 45-car train loaded with 1,350 tons of relief supplies was to have left July 17 from <LOCATION> Babanousa </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Kordofan </LOCATION>, north of the war zone, en route to <LOCATION> Aweil </LOCATION>, a major center for displaced people in the south. Days later, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said the train would not leave without assurances from the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> that it would not be attacked. The train is to carry food and medicines to places held by both the rebels and the government. Politics also have interfered with the relief operation. Operations were suspended temporarily after a military coup June 30 ousted the civilian government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said the new leader, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Bashir </PERSON>, `` took great pains to reaffirm the support of the new government to continuing Operation Lifeline <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>.'' The government previously put obstacles in the way, claiming agencies wanted to feed rebels trying to take over <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Rebel commanders also have used food as a weapon, even shooting at relief planes flying into rebel areas.
