<HEAD>Opium Poppies Bloom Near Hospital for Drug Addicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's largest illegal poppy field has been discovered near a hospital that treats drug addicts, news reports said Saturday. About 1,000 opium-producing poppies, used to make heroin and morphine, were found Friday after a nurse, not realizing what they were, picked some to decorate a room at <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Gaustad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Verdens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gang </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper reported. Another nurse recognized the flowers and called police, who destroyed the well-tended field, said the paper. Chief nurse <PERSON> Anne-Lise </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergenheim </PERSON> told the paper that the hospital patients, who are closely supervised, could not have tended the field `` unless they worked at night wearing miners' lamps. The flowers usually grow in warmer climates, but they can also thrive during <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s short growing season. Police said they had no idea who planted the flowers.
