<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-Chicken     07-29 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Chicken,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush And Democrats Working On Savings And Loan Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional Democrats are engaged in a game of chicken over how to finance the multibillion-dollar bailout of hundreds of failed savings institutions. On Friday, the squawking began. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> paraded before television cameras at three separate news conferences to outline their views, one day after <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators sealed a compromise deal on the landmark legislation. The president favors a complex scheme to pay for the bailout by borrowing the money through a new, quasi-private agency. That has the advantage of keeping $ 50 billion in <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L spending out of the budget deficit, which, if it goes too high, triggers automatic spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman law. Democrats support the plan adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference, which they say is cheaper and more honest, to borrow the money through the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. However, that would balloon the deficit over the next three years. Democrats evade the automatic spending cuts by simply waiving Gramm-Rudman. Republicans say the administration's method keeps the spending discipline of Gramm-Rudman in place. Democrats say <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is just engaging in a more subtle kind of subterfuge. Both agree that the other side is holding up urgent legislation needed to staunch the industry's hemorrhaging and neither wants to be blamed for that. The stakes are high. S & amp; Ls are losing an estimated $ 20 million a day, $ 833,333 an hour, $ 13,888 a minute and $ 231.48 a second. That's a lot of blame to shoulder and it hardly seems worth it for either side to get tarred over what at first glance seems like nothing more than an accounting question. But, the issue is important, not now, but over the next several years, because it will have a major role in the annual jousting over how to balance the budget, through spending cuts or tax increases. Even though both plans alleviate the danger of an automatic spending cut, politically, their effect could n't be more different. Democrats are betting that if they win on <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L spending, and the reported budget deficit approaches the record set during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years instead of getting better, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wo n't be willing to endure the kind of drastic spending cuts that would be needed to reduce it. They believe he will feel that much more pressure to abandon his `` Read my lips: No new taxes'' pledge repeated over and over during the 1988 campaign. The issue comes to a head this week when the S & amp; L compromise package reaches the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which must approve it before it goes to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his signature. Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, has vowed `` unless God palsies my voice'' to protect the deficit-reduction law that bears his name. <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> has the signatures of 41 senators, including his own, pledging to reject the S & amp; L compromise. Under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s rules, that's enough to block it. On the other hand, if <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> is successful the legislation bounces back to the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference, where majority Democrats prevail. So, the two sides are locked in a stalemate. Either can tie up the legislation, but neither has the stomach to do that for very long. The winner likely will be the side that is most successful at blaming the other for delay. Expect the squawking to grow louder.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Skidmore </PERSON> has covered the savings and loan crisis for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1987.
</TEXT>
