<FIRST>r w AM-HUDOverpayments 1stLd-Writethru a0507 07-29 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Overpayments, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Audits Critical of Projects Tied to Former HUD Officials, Consultant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf to say last week, sted this week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two new <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> audits say rent subsidies were improperly inflated by $ 6 million for two housing projects involving former agency officials. The internal audits completed this month by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general found that local housing authorities in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Gastonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, allowed a mortgage company to establish the rents for the projects, a violation of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> guidelines. The Tulsa project, Windsong Apartments, is owned by a partnership that includes four former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials _ <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Winn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> and <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Queenan </PERSON>. All four also had stakes in projects reviewed as part of a nationwide audit released in April that cited excessive rents as one of several problems afflicting the Section 8 Moderate Rehabilitation Program. The <LOCATION> Gastonia </LOCATION> development, Four Seasons Apartments, is owned by a group that hired <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island-based </LOCATION> consultant <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegal </PERSON> to help obtain the lucrative rehabilitation subsidies. Ms. <PERSON> Siegal </PERSON> was among the lesser-known, but more successful, consultants cited in the earlier report, which found that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> was being overcharged more than $ 400 million over the 15-year life of the rehabilitation subsidies because of inflated rents. The mortgage company that established the rents, <ORGANIZATION> Benton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, also has figured prominently in an ongoing investigation of abuses at the agency. The company co-insured the projects with <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. All the audits noted that former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials had won a significant share of the rehabilitation money and that prominent Republican consultants were successful in steering money to their clients. Since the report in April, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has been the subject of internal, congressional and <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigations. Mismanagement and abuses have been found in a number of the multibillion-dollar agency's programs. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> suspended the Moderate Rehabilitation Program. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in its budget bill for <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> next year, included no new funding for the program. The two new audits obtained last week under the Freedom of Information Act were not part of the nationwide review. The audit of the Tulsa project, completed July 11, found that the <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> housing authority misinterpreted <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> guidelines and allowed <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> to calculate the rents for the 202-unit Windsong complex. As a result, auditors said, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> already had paid more than $ 200,000 in excess of what it should have since the subsidies began in 1987 and could overpay by as much as $ 3.4 million over the life of the contract unless the subsidies are reduced. The findings of the <LOCATION> Gastonia </LOCATION> audit, completed July 24, were very similar. Investigators found that the <ORGANIZATION> Gastonia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> allowed <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> to set the rents, which auditors said were calculated with a faulty formula and included ineligible costs. As a result, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had paid $ 63,000 in excessive subsidies from late 1987 through March and over the term of the contract will overpay rents by more than $ 2.5 million unless the subsidies are recalculated. In both the <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gastonia </LOCATION> audits, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> urged the local housing officials and regional <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials to recalculate the subsidies and to recover the overpaid amounts. That process is just getting under way.
