<HEAD>Deafness of Three Suspects Complicates Murder Prosecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judicial system is struggling with communications and legal challenges in trying three deaf men charged with murdering a service station attendant in 1976. Police and prosecutors have used sign-language interpreters to communicate with the defendants, but one defense attorney says that may be inadequate to convey the nuances of court testimony and cross-examination. Sign language is n't even satisfactory for friendly meetings with her client, said <PERSON> Tricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, a public defender. `` There's always the fear that he does n't understand,'' she said last week. The case involves the slaying of <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Deland </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, a service station attendant in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, who was killed in a Feb. 3, 1976, holdup that netted the bandits $ 100 to $ 200 cash. <PERSON> Ricki </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> Lakeland </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Augustine </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, are charged with first-degree murder in the case. The men are being held without bail in the <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION> pending their trial, tentatively set for September. Ms. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said she's attempting to negotiate a plea agreement in <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> case. Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said plea negotiations with <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> are under way. The case was listed as unsolved until mid-January, when detectives got a tip. The information resulted in the arrest of <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> in Febraury and <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> in June. Since the men were arrested, police, prosecutors and defense attorneys have had to balance protecting their rights against the problems created by their handicaps. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Deaf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, has acted as a sign-language interpreter for police and prosecutors in dealing with the men, who have varying degrees of communication skills. Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said interpreters `` have to be unbiased and be able to walk the fence'' and be careful that what they sign is an accurate translation of what is said. But she admits there are drawbacks. For example, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Language </ORGANIZATION> does n't have a sign for `` weapon.'' There are signs for `` gun,'' and `` knife,'' but the language lacks a symbol for the general concept. Ms. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> represents <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON>, who can hear sounds with the use of hearing aids. She worries that his rights have been violated and her effectiveness as a lawyer has been diminished because of his partial deafness. After reviewing the tapes of his interrogation by police, Ms. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said she feels the interpreter may have summarized the questions asked by police and done the same with her client's answers `` It is very different when I'm conversing with a hearing client. You can convey certain ideas with tones and inflections. I leave an interview with him not feeling satisfied that I communicated with him,'' she said. If the case goes to trial, it could be a logistical nightmare to make sure the defendants understand what is happening in the courtroom. Ms. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, the public defender has suggested using computer terminals to print out questions and answers for the defendants. `` It's the only way I can see where he would get a fair trial,'' she said.
