<HEAD>Jaruzelski Resigns As Party Chief, Replaced by Rakowski</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Politburo members and party
secretaries sacked by the plenum. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``Jaruzelski, who...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> resigned today as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and was replaced by the outgoing prime minister, a politician who has become a champion of hard-line forces in the party. The moves came at a two-day <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> plenum called to debate the future of the party, which has been deeply divided by policy disputes and parliamentary elections in which many of its candidates were trounced. The plenum also dropped five of the 18 Politburo members and three of the nine party secretaries, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> announced. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, who had led the party since 1981, promised to give up his post as party chief before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> narrowly elected him to the new office of president on July 19. But some observers were surprised that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> elected outgoing Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> by a 4-1 margin to replace <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> as party leader. The selection of the 62-year-old <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> culminated a remarkable political rise by an official who only joined the Politburo in December 1987 after having been dropped from the government in 1985. In recent months <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> has been roundly criticized for his government's handling of the economy. A party member with a long reputation as a reformer, in the past year <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> has become the champion of hard-line elements in the party and those concerned about the rising influence of Solidarity. Earlier today, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s government came under renewed criticism for its economic performance. Inflation has climbed into triple digits and basic goods such as meat, bread and sugar have been in short supply in recent weeks. A plan by <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> to sharply raise food prices Aug. 1 has been criticized as not properly prepared. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> accepted with one abstention the resignation of <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> from the office of first secretary,'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. Moments later, the plenum elected <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> 171 to 41, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. The only remaining question facing the plenum, which began Friday, appeared to be who will replace <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> as prime minister. Potential candidates appeared to be Politburo member <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Baka </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ireneusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sekula </PERSON>, now deputy prime minister and a <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> loyalist, or <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON>, the leader of the allied <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> hinted at the plenum Friday that he would not hold the party leadership much longer and said a full congress of the 2-million-member party should be held soon. `` I am standing before you still, for the moment, in a double role,'' said <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, referring to his election as president. He challenged fellow Communists to decide `` what we stand for.'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said the plenum today adopted a resolution declaring the party's willingness to work with the independent Solidarity trade union movement and with the 260 Solidarity lawmakers chosen by the voters in June. As a result of the country's most democratic elections since World War II, the formerly banned Solidarity now controls 99 out of 100 seats in the new freely elected <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and 161 of the 460 seats in the Sejm, or parliament. Many party-backed candidates suffered humiliating defeats in the election. The resolution reaffirmed the party's January decision to legalize Solidarity and `` defined conditions'' needed to improve the economy, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said, without elaborating. Earlier today, the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> information policy director, <PERSON> Slawomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabkowski </PERSON>, told the plenum the party is changing too quickly for more doctrinaire members, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The speaker said possibilities should be created for those who are disappointed with the party ... and those who do not identify with the direction of changes to leave,'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. But <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Majka </PERSON>, the editor of the generally hard-line party daily <ORGANIZATION> Trybuna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ludu </ORGANIZATION>, said recent talk about the party's future is `` unsettling to all people, not only party members,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Majka </PERSON> said the party must maintain its `` rational'' approach in trying to solve <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s problems. The discussion included sharp criticism of the party's performance in the elections and of the government's handling of the economy In another development, Politburo member <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Baka </PERSON> quit as party secretary in charge of the economy after delivering a speech criticizing <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s administration. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> handed in his government's resignation when the new Parliament was seated. <PERSON> Baka </PERSON> was considered a likely candidate to succeed <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> as prime minister.
