<HEAD>Deng Says He Does Not Approve of `Great Democracy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> said in an essay publicized Saturday that he does not approve of `` great democracy'' but that `` small democracy'' is needed to keep in touch with the masses. Allowing the masses to supervise the rulers `` is better than not having supervision,'' wrote the 84-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, who has crushed three populist democracy movements in his decade of rule. The last time was in June, when he ordered an army attack on student protesters. `` If we do n't accept supervision and expand the democratic life of the party and country, we will be divorced from the masses and commit great errors,'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> wrote in the essay summarized on the television evening news. The report said the essay would appear in the next issue of the magazine Party Building. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> added, `` We do not approve of great democracy. Great democracy is avoidable, and this requires having small democracy.'' He did not explain what he meant by the terms, but `` great democracy'' appeared to be a reference to the kind of unfettered debate that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> denounced in the recent student protests as leading to anarchy. In past writings, he also has rejected Western-style parliamentary democracy as bourgeois. By small democracy, he apparently was referring to controlled expressions of opinion that do not challenge the power of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He wrote that the party should be supervised by the masses and by the eight officially approved non-Communist parties that are permitted to exist. Most important, the party must police itself, he said. `` Whether or not the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is qualified to lead depends on our party itself ... on our party's ideology and work style,'' he wrote. The party, meanwhile, announced it was issuing a new book called `` Deng Xiaoping Over 28 Years,'' written by his colleagues and commemorating his `` glorious and outstanding achievements.'' Publication of the essay and the book were part of a new high profile, tinged with adulation, for the aging leader, who had been in semi-retirement. He re-emerged to lead the June crackdown on the student protesters, and since then a series of books and a movie about him have appeared. His name appears in newspaper headlines daily, and millions of Chinese nationwide are being required to study a speech he made on crushing the student `` rebellion.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said in the past that he did not want the mass adulation revolutionary leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> received in his last years. The current campaign of Dengist admiration falls far short of that, but many Chinese have begun drawing a parallel. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> had been expected to retire from his last official posts, as head of the state and party military affairs commissions, later this year. But Western diplomats say they consider that unlikely given the army's new prominence and power. In other developments, Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> told a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> newspaper publisher <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is willing to maintain good relations with <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> despite `` recent difficulties'' but that the future of relations `` depends on the French side.'' The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Li </PERSON> spoke in a meeting with <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yongju </PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> froze its relations with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to protest the crackdown on the protesters, and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since has protested that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> gave refuge to some fugitive student and intellectual leaders.
