<HEAD>Amoco And Poland Sign Oil Exploration Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has signed an agreement to explore for oil in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, according to a published report. Under the contract, signed Friday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> and the state-owned Polish Oil and <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will conduct a 12-month joint study of geological and geophysical data on roughly 40 percent of the country, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday. If the exploration indicates potential oil reserves, <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> and Polish Oil and Gas would negotiate a second contract that would enable the Chicago-based company to drill exploratory wells and ultimately produce oil. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> employees will go to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> next month, and <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> and Gas employees will eventually come to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production company's <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters to study the data. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>, the fifth-biggest U.S.-based energy company, has been conducting a similar study in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> produces only 3,000 barrels of oil a day, according to <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> estimates. By comparison, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> pumps 63,000 barrels a day. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> consumes an estimated 540,000 barrels of oil a day, much of that obtained from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in exchange for machinery and other goods. But the potential for oil is indicated by <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s abundance of coal _ the two hydrocarbons are often found in proximity to one another. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has n't explored intensively for oil for at least 45 years, and thus may have missed deposits detectable with today's sophisticated equipment, said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Munk </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>'s manager of foreign affairs `` It's a problem of technical capabilities and money,'' said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Szczurowski </PERSON>, the economic attache at the Polish commercial consular's office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
