<HEAD>Syrians And Christians Clash Across A Virtual Ghost City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> gunners battled with howitzers and rocket launchers Saturday over the ruins of a virtual ghost city, deserted by more than a million people fleeing fighting that has left hundreds dead. Police said eight people were killed and 42 wounded in overnight and morning exchanges across the divided capital, where 1.5 million people once lived. `` My city is dying. I'll die with it. I wo n't leave,'' <PERSON> Ihsan </PERSON> <PERSON> Salam </PERSON>, a retired civil servant, said with tears in his eyes. `` I'll stay here. If I have to die, I'll die in dignity in my apartment, in my bed. I do n't want to live as a refugee,'' said the 70-year-old Sunni Moslem who lives in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Zasrif </LOCATION> district. The summer wind kicked up dust storms in the dirty streets, and cats chased rats across piles of stinking garbage littering the once-fashionable <LOCATION> Hamra </LOCATION> commercial thoroughfare. Banks, restaurants, stores and offices were closed, and the once swarming streets were almost deserted. Fires blazed out of control and palls of thick black smoke billowed from gaping holes in apartment buildings. <PERSON> Salam </PERSON> is among only about 250,000 people still living in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> after more than four months of almost daily artillery duels. Saturday's casualties raised the overall toll to 502 killed and 2,056 wounded in the 19-week confrontation between Christian army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s troops and Syrian forces. The fighting erupted after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> imposed a naval blockade on illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in an effort to recover around $ 100 million annually in lost customs revenues. The Syrians joined the Moslem militias shelling the Christian enclave north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in retaliation and blocked its land entrances. The Sy