<HEAD>Chileans Show Little Interest in Constitutional Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an unprecedented show of unity, both the military government and its political foes are encouraging Chileans to approve democratic reforms of the constitution in a referendum Sunday. Most Chileans, however, have shown little interest in the vote, apparently believing the changes will pass even with a small turnout. Voting is mandatory, but government officials and opposition leaders still fear many of the 7.6 million registered voters will stay home. President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has sent all 16 of his Cabinet ministers on tours of provincial cities to explain the proposed reforms and ask people to vote. The head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, warned that those failing to vote will be prosecuted and may be fined $ 100. That's a lot of money in a country where about a third of the labor force earns the legal mimimum salary of $ 66 a month or less. The referendum asks Chileans to approve or reject as a package 54 changes in the 1980 constitution, which was written by the military. The changes include easing restrictions on Marxist activity, which has been banned. It dilutes the government's power in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by increasing the number of seats from 36 to 48 and leaving the government-appointed bloc at nine. It also adds another civilian member to a powerful, military-dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Other changes would eliminate the presidential power to send Chileans into exile and to dissolve the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Requirements for future constitutional reform would be eased. Both the government and opposition agreed to the text of the proposed changes. Officials said the proposals were viewed as `` democratizing'' the constitution, although the opposition had repeatedly said they were insufficient. `` The constitution continues to be anti-democratic, but it's a first step which will allow us all to build together a really democratic institutional system,'' said <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, a prominent Socialist leader. Constitutional experts and political leaders had said public apathy during the campaign stemmed from the widespread belief the proposed changes would be approved even with a small turnout. `` There's nothing dramatic about this referendum,'' said <PERSON> Edgardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Boeninger </PERSON>, vice president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest in the opposition. `` There is no one to beat this time,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He also said Chileans had displayed little interest because they were ill informed and considered the changes very complex. Nearly all the major political parties and the government urged approval of the changes in 40-second television spots broadcast by all the country's stations. The spots were allocated at no charge to opposition parties. About the only controversy of the campaign broke out when the government censored at least 10 opposition television spots, claiming they were illegal. It said they were intended as party propaganda _ not to clarify the referendum. The country's last referendum was Oct. 5, and turnout was 97 percent. At issue was whether <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s rule should be extended until 1997. The extension was overwhelmingly rejected.
