<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s agony began nearly 20 years ago when pro-American generals ousted a neutralist prince. Since then, millions have been killed, made homeless or fled the killing field that their homeland has become. The 1970 coup against Cambodian leader Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> set off a cycle of national devastation that an international conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> is now trying to reverse. Under Gen. <PERSON> Lon </PERSON> <PERSON> Nol </PERSON>, the U.S.-backed coup leaders took on the communists of neighboring <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and their <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> allies, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, in a five-year war. Some people called it a `` sideshow'' to the Vietnam War. But it killed an estimated 1 million people as ground troops engaged in fierce combat and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> launched one of the most intense aerial bombardments in history. On April 17, 1975, the black-clad <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> marched into the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> capital and began to herd its 2 million people into the countryside at gunpoint. <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Year Zero'' had begun: society was to be totally cleansed and all resisters eliminated in the Southeast Asian nation. The most conservative estimates say hundreds of thousands were executed or died of diseases and hunger in <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> labor camps. The current <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government claims 3.3 million died as leader <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> turned on `` class enemies'' who included children, the handicapped, and anyone who spoke a foreign language. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s 1978 invasion rid the country of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> but spawned another conflict. From jungle bases along the Thai-Cambodian border, a three-party coalition led by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> mounted a guerrilla campaign against the Vietnamese and the new <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government they had installed. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> formed part of the coalition. More than a quarter-million civilians remain in sprawling, vulnerable camps along the embattled frontier. Fighting in the interior and uncertainty about the future hampers development in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, one of the world's poorest countries. With <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> promising to pull out its remaining forces in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by the end of September, threats of more bloodshed looms. The powerful <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> could attempt a comeback and carry out another reign of terror.
