'' <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON> said he still thinks he will win the right to face <PERSON> Young </PERSON> again. Young, who has n't faced a real challenge since his first bid for mayor in 1973, has been under attack this year. Critics accuse him of failing to reverse the city's chronic crime and unemployment problems. On a more personal level, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> agreed earlier this year to pay child support following a highly publicized paternity suit in which blood tests confirmed he fathered the 6-year-old son of a former city employee. Even with a perception of <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s vulnerability, <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>' entry into the race baffled some observers who question why he would give up his seniority in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where he is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> watchdog panel. `` I am very puzzled,'' <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said. `` He's been around a long time and could really do a lot of good for <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> in that position,'' in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> believes <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> may be laying the groundwork for 1993, when <PERSON> Young </PERSON> is expected to step down. `` I think this is going to be a showcase for'93 ... the post-Young era,'' he said. How long <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>' popularity will hold out is another question. `` I think <PERSON> John </PERSON> has always been a man of symbols, always engaged in symbolic events,'' <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> said, referring to <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>' opposition to the Vietnam War, his involvement in former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s impeachment and his support of a holiday honoring the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` Whatever