<HEAD>New Polish Party Leader Caps Comeback</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The selection of <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> to lead <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> through an era of political upheaval culminates the remarkable comeback of a man ousted from government in 1985. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>, chosen Saturday by a divided <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, only joined the party's ruling Politburo on Dec. 15, 1987. Although he supports a radical restructuring of the economy, he acknowledges he is now linked more with the party's conservative elements than its reformist wing. Under <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s leadership as premier, the government ended gasoline rationing and legalized the black market in foreign currencies. But in his nine months as prime minister, the economy has deteriorated and <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> made little progress in winning the hearts of Solidarity supporters who remember him as one of the union's scrappiest foes. With inflation now in triple digits and many basic commodities such as meat, bread and sugar in short supply, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s promotion to the head party post in a 171-41 vote might seem peculiar. He became deputy prime minister Feb. 12, 1981, but his abrasiveness made him enemies. He lost that post in November 1985 when several hard-liners were dumped from the government. From 1985 to 1987, he held a largely ceremonial position as deputy speaker of the Sejm, or Parliament. He was one of 33 senior officials who ran unopposed for <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in June but failed to capture even half the votes. One party member in the debate Saturday said only 35 percent of Polish people voice confidence in the government now, compared with 72 percent shortly after <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> took office. But <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s calls for the party to stand firm in the face of its difficulties apparently have appealed to party conservatives and those in the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who feel threatened by the rise of Solidarity's influence. The union won 260 of 261 parliament seats it contested in June. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> succeeds <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, who resigned Saturday as he had promised to do before being elected president. A man of peasant origins who rose to become one of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leading journalists From 1958 through 1982, <PERSON> Rakowksi </PERSON> was editor of Polityka, a Communist-controlled but generally liberal weekly that was considered even daring through the 1970s. The 62-year-old <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> was named prime minister Sept. 27 and formed his government Oct. 14. He was rebuffed by opposition members he sought to enlist. Although <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> in January urged legalization of Solidarity after its seven-year ban, he did not take an active role in the talks that followed. Solidarity was legalized again in April. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> became unpopular with leaders of Solidarity during its 16-month legal period in 1980-81. One of his first acts as prime minister was to announce the closing of the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, Solidarity's birthplace, in a move many union members interpreted as a personal vendetta. During Solidarity's early months as a legal group, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> headed the government's committee for trade unions and served as the government's chief negotiator with Solidarity. He also played a major role in defending the suppression of the union after the introduction of martial law Dec. 13, 1981. Born in the village of <LOCATION> Kowalewek </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Dec. 1, 1926, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> was a teen-age laborer during the Nazi occupation of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and served in the Polish army from the time of the liberation until 1949. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1946 and attended the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. In a widely circulated memorandum on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political situation written before his Politburo appointment, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> backed further democratization and economic reform. But he also urged the party to stake out more clearly its ideological differences with Solidarity. In a newspaper interview last week, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> said the party should resist attempts to divide it. He called on the party to become `` a pragmatic leftist party of the 21st century.'' But he added: `` To be pragmatic does not mean to disrespect Marxism and the historical achievements of Polish socialists and communists.''
</TEXT>
