<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Opposition     07-29 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Opposition,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organize First Opposition in Soviet Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first organized opposition in the Soviet parliament in nearly 70 years was formed Saturday by 368 legislators who gathered to plan their strategy for greater political and economic reforms. Even the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the historic event could be described as `` the birth of the Soviet opposition.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> called the organization `` left-radical.'' In another development, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> joined the two other Baltic republics, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, in declaring itself `` sovereign'' with the right to veto Soviet laws on its territory, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. Among the members of the opposition group are human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>; maverick Communist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>; <PERSON> Vitaly </PERSON> <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON>, editor of the reform magazine Ogonyoky; and economist <PERSON> Gavriil </PERSON> <PERSON> Popov </PERSON>. It will operate under the title Inter-Regional Deputies' Group. <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotova </PERSON>, who participated in the meeting but is not a legislator, said, `` Our desired aim is to have the equivalent of a Western party.'' The Left Socialist Revolutionaries was the last opposition party to survive the Bolshevik purges following the 1917 revolution. It was suppressed in 1922. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has ordered many reforms since coming to power in 1985 but has strongly opposed allowing an alternative party to the Communists. Leaders of the new organization said enough contributions have been received to begin publishing a newspaper. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Bocharov </PERSON>, a deputy from suburban <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputy will start with a circulation of 300,000 and sell for about 80 cents a copy. That is more than 18 times the cost of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda but considerably less than a Soviet fashion magazine. Historian <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Afanasiev </PERSON>, a deputy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said the group will meet Sunday and hopes to reach agreement on a platform. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> predicted <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> would be elected leader but <PERSON> Afanasiev </PERSON> indicated the group is leaning toward a governing council with several deputies. The organization is still a small minority in the 2,250-seat <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, the Soviet parliament. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, a deputy from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, said most of his colleagues from the three Baltic republics had left <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the weekend but when they returned they could add up to 140 members to the group. It was not clear how many of the opposition deputies are also members of the smaller legislative branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> called the Supreme Soviet. The group could have its most immediate effect on the political process by proposing laws. The Supreme Soviet gained that power this spring but so far it has considered only proposals put forth by the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> deputy <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Stankevich </PERSON>, writing in the first issue of The People's Deputy, said that fears instilled by years of political tyranny made people shy away from an open opposition. <PERSON> Popov </PERSON> opened Saturday's meeting in the crowded auditorium of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Filmmakers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> with a call to bring reform through legal changes instead of what he called the government's `` spontaneous approach'' to crises. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the group has a place in the reform process but reported some legislators `` have expressed the fear that in this complex time for the country, when unity of action is required, this ` left-radical group' might turn into some kind of opposition.'' Organizers of the group said it has been tolerated by the government bureaucracy and was not allowed to meet in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>. Among issues discussed Saturday were proposals that would give enterprises more independence and allow Soviets living abroad who were stripped of their citizenship to reclaim it. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> parliament's declaration of sovereignty means that `` laws of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> will go into effect on the territory of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> only after their ratification by the highest organ of government in the republic.'' When <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> declared its sovereignty last November, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> called the action unconstitutional. On Thursday, however, the Supreme Soviet gave preliminary approval to resolutions that would give <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> economic independence by Jan. 1. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> has tried to assert independence on issues of public concern, such as environmental protection. <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> followed <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s example this summer after its Sajudis reform group won a majority of the republic's seats in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s first contested elections for parliament.
