<HEAD>With AM-Party Switchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans held a grand old party Saturday to welcome their latest convert, Rep. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, who defected from the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> ranks earlier this week. `` I know how hard it is to be a Southern conservative Democrat. My conscience is now clear,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> told about 150 cheering Republicans. `` I have now made my decision and it is the right one for the people of this state.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced the three-term <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> congressman's party change Friday <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> was the third Democrat in three days to make the switch. Also changing parties were retiring <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> _ widely considered a mayoral prospect for the capital _ and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> <PERSON> McKeithen </PERSON>. `` That party has shut out <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and that party has lost <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>,'' he said. `` I can no longer be a member of that party.'' Republican leaders raved about their newest congressman. Former Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> `` Footsie'' <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> called it the `` first crack in the dam'' of recruiting from the Democratic ranks. `` He really is a phenomenon,'' said party activist <PERSON> Emaline </PERSON> <PERSON> Holleman </PERSON> of <PERSON> Wynne </PERSON>. `` I think <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> will bring us votes,'' she said. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 47, and his wife, <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON>, were cheered by an audience that waved small <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags and swayed to a Dixieland band. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZ