<HEAD>Rain in the West</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Rain and thunderstorms moved across parts of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> on Saturday, bringing up to 5 inches to some areas, while rain in the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> brought relief to the Corn Belt. Rain was measured at 5 inches just west of <LOCATION> Virgil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, with 4 inches in the <LOCATION> Piermont </LOCATION> area and 3 inches in the town of <LOCATION> Hecla </LOCATION>. Large hail and 3 inches of rain was reported east of <LOCATION> Langford </LOCATION>, S.D. Generous rainfall was also reported over parts of central and southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. One to 4 inches was reported from <LOCATION> Browns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> along the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Nearly 3 -RCB- inches of rain fell in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn </LOCATION>. The showers and thunderstorms extended from upper <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> through northwest <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> into southwest <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> by afternoon. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were developing from <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> into the central Gulf Coast region. Showers and thunderstorms were also developing along the eastern slopes of the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. Temperatures were in the 80s or 90s across much of the nation. Readings were in the 60s and 70s from the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> through the lower Great Lakes and parts of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Temperatures were in the 50s over parts of the upper Great Lakes. Temperatures were also in the 70s through parts of the intermountain region. Temperatures reached into the 90s to around 100 degrees across the desert Southwest. Temperatures in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> reached 93 degrees tying the record high temperature for the date set in 1986. The low in the nation was 36 degrees at <LOCATION> Truckee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57 degrees at <LOCATION> Ironwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to 101 degrees at Needles and <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The forecast for Sunday called for showers and thunderstorms scattered from the lower Great Lakes through the lower <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> valleys, the middle and lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and into the central and eastern <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region with showers most numerous across parts of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. Late afternoon showers and thunderstorms were expected over parts of western <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, north central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and the southern high Plains. High temperatures were forecast for the 80s or 90s across much of the nation Sunday. Highs in the 70s were expected along the central and northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and from the Great Lakes into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Highs between 100 and 105 degrees were expected from central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> into the middle <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and up to 110 degrees across the desert Southwest.
