<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique     07-29 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Veers Away from Marxism with New Economic Policies.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Machungo </PERSON> outlined the ruling party's new political and economic policies Saturday and said an independent economy is necessary to build socialism. The outline indicated that the party _ the Front for the Liberation of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Frelimo </LOCATION> _ is moving away from Marxism and central planning. <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION> has governed <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> under a one-party, Marxist-Leninist policy since gaining power after the country gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. But its policy document, presented last week to <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION>'s first national congress since 1983, dropped all references to Marxism. The document described the party as socialist. It also said <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION> is open to all Mozambicans and is not just a worker-peasant alliance. The party congress has already been presented with its <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendations to open ranks to businessmen, property owners, shopkeepers and religious believers. The congress convened July 24 and is to close Monday. During Saturday's session <PERSON> Machungo </PERSON> said, `` The process of building socialism requires the creation of an independent and advanced economy.'' He said the effort also would require `` the active participation of various property regimes _ state-owned, cooperative and peasant family property, and private or joint-venture forms of property.'' Several years ago the government began opening the economy, encouraging private enterprise and foreign investments mainly to meet requirements for loans from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. About half of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s 14 million people are wholly or partly dependent on donated food and 1.6 million are refugees from the 12-year-old civil war that has left hundreds of thousands dead. <PERSON> Machungo </PERSON> said the major change from the social and economic directives of 1983 `` is that today <ORGANIZATION> Frelimo </ORGANIZATION> does not attempt to establish target figures for every sector of the economy. Instead the directives set out basic policy goals.'' He said the new directives `` lay heavy stress on peasant family agriculture rather than on state farms,'' but that state farms still have an important role in producing exports. <PERSON> Machungo </PERSON> said the directives also call for `` increased labor productivity and for the implementation of the principle of paying more to those who work more, carry out their duties better and attain the best indexes of efficiency.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said it would allow private schools, outlawed in 1975, to be re-established because the government was unable to provide education for all of the country's children. It said rebels have destroyed or forced the closure of 2,699 primary schools in rural areas.
