<HEAD>Rafsanjani Wins Landslide Majority, Sheibani Concedes Defeat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> was elected president by a landslide majority, according to official returns announced Saturday. Government-run <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> won 13,468,355 out of 14,192,802 votes cast Friday in 192 out of 198 regions, or about 95 percent. It also said 97 percent of the voters approved constitutional amendments boosting the president's executive power. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio said <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s only opponent, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> deputy <PERSON> Abass </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheibani </PERSON> from the token opposition party, the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, won 483,050 votes, or about 3 percent. <PERSON> Sheibani </PERSON> conceded defeat in a letter to <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> read over the radio and was quoted as saying: `` I congratulate you on your election, which was achieved with a definite vote.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official media did not say how many of the country's 25 million voters age 16 or older turned out to vote, or when full results would be reported. About 17 million people voted in last year's parliamentary elections. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s main opposition group, the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warriors </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement released at its headquarters in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, that turnout was low <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, a so-called pragmatist in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s religious hierarchy, will be the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>'s fourth president. He will succeed <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, who was chosen supreme leader after the death June 3 of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruholla </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> is expected to move toward restoring links with the West and liberalizing <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s economy to help the country's reconstruction after the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, which was suspended by a cease-fire last August The constitutional amendments approved in the election do away with the post of prime minister and put the president in charge of the government, answerable only to the 270-seat Majlis, or parliament. The changes are designed to eliminate competing power centers that have for years paralyzed the government and blocked economic reforms.
