cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE BEZICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Disciples of Christ -RRB- Saturday endorsed a working partnership with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>, despite criticism from some members that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is too liberal. Delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Disciples of Christ -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> approved a resolution for full communion between the two churches, including mutual recognition of members and clergy. The resolution means the churches will recognize each other's members as believers in a single common faith, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the president of the council on Christian unity He said they will also work to coordinate the two churches' social services and community functions About 6,000 delegates attended the first day of business of the five-day <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Disciples of Christ -RRB- General Assembly, officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> passed a similar resolution at its national convention in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, a month ago. `` This is not a merger. It's not a uniting of the churches' structure,'' <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> said `` This is setting up a common acknowledgement of each other.'' The move means the two congregations can attend the same worship services, but <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> says local churches will maintain their own identities. The Disciples of Christ and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> base their faith on the same Christian doctrine, <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> said. The two organizations already work together in much of their missionary endeavors, but they differ in some worship practices and church policies, he said. One of those policies is a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> clause that forbids church boards from considering sexual orientation of its ministers. That means the church officially allows homosexuals to become ministers and forbids member churches from discriminating against them. `` In putting our stamp of approval on this, we are putting our stamp of approval on homosexuality,'' said <PERSON> Bethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Nason </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kan </PERSON>. Her statements against the resolution brought a round of applause from delegates. The resolution does not mention the issue of homosexuality. Disciples of Christ delegate <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spearman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, charged the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> is `` far to the left, both political and ecumenically.'' But <PERSON> Crow </PERSON> said the differences in social beliefs are as common within the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Disciples of Christ -RRB- as they are between the two denominations. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> allows for unity in diversity but that diversity need not divide us,'' he said. Disciples President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Humbert </PERSON