<HEAD>Military Regime Gives Itself Broad Powers Over Judiciary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's new military ruler further consolidated power Saturday by decreeing broad judicial powers for himself. The order gives Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> el-Bashir power to appoint the chief justice and senior judges. He can also commute death sentences and issue reprieves without explanation. The decree, which <PERSON> el-Bashir </PERSON> signed as head of the ruling 15-officer junta, named him `` supreme constitutional authority in the country.'' Shortly after Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON>'s civilian government was overthrown in a bloodless coup on June 30, el-Bashir made himself prime minister, minister of defense and military commander-in-chief of this East African nation. He dissolved <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s 36 political parties and banned all newspapers and magazines. In the past, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s chief justice was elected by other judges. Senior judges were nominated by the chief justice and appointed by a five-member <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> El-Bashir </PERSON> has accused officials of the former government and many political party members of corruption. He has said those accused of wrongdoing will stand trial. <PERSON> El-Mahdi </PERSON> has been imprisoned with about 40 former senior political figures.
