<HEAD>Students Create Union to Push Democratic Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates attending the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Saturday created a fledgling national student union aimed at pressuring <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for democratic reforms. After lengthy debate and overnight revisions, delegates ratified a constitution creating the All-America Chinese Student Union. `` It's not perfect enough, but it's really a very good start,'' said <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Jain </PERSON>, chairman of the congress. Creation of the union was the main focus of the three-day congress, which attracted Chinese students from across the country, a spokesman for the congress said. The union will coordinate efforts to bring pressure on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to adopt pro-democratic reforms, said <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> <PERSON> Minxin </PERSON>, 31, a graduate student from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and spokesman for the congress. After ratifying the constitution, the congress voted on a variety of proposed projects for the union to undertake. The projects include lobbying governments for economic sanctions against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, organizing boycotts against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and assuming joint management with the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> the weekly newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. The paper was founded by a group of journalists in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on June 9, 1989. Many of the proposals have been tried by individual student organizations before, <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> said, `` but now, with the establishment of this union, there is a legitimacy, a broad-based legitimacy to these efforts ... and conceivably we will attract more support from <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> students across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The union's creation was brought about by the June 3-4 army attack in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in which hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators were killed in Tiananmen Square, <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> said. Chinese students in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> believed there had to be other ways to change the government in their native country, <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> said. `` Why not choose another less costly message, such as lobbying for these individual measures?'' <PERSON> Pei </PERSON> said. `` Conceivably Chinese students will work through this organization to voice their pro-democratic ideas and opinions and also voice their protests against the human rights violations by the Chinese government,'' he said.
