<HEAD>Billy Graham Addresses 90,000 People in Soccer Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, on his fourth visit to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, preached to an estimated 90,000 people Saturday in a <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> soccer stadium. The stadium seats 70,000, so many people stood on the field as <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, speaking from a platform, told the crowd, `` God knows everything'' and `` salvation is through Christ.'' Organizers said it was the largest crowd ever gathered in the stadium. The predominantly young audience frequently cheered <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. He spoke in English and the sermon was translated into Hungarian. `` I see we have a capacity crowd here. This is an indication of the spiritual yearning and hunger,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. He did not make any political comments but when he arrived Tusday he said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s religious life was `` at a great historical turning point.'' `` I believe our present visit is another sign of this new spirit of openness and change,'' he said. The state news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> published a brief report on <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s service and said among those attending the event were <PERSON> Matyas </PERSON> <PERSON> Szueros </PERSON>, the speaker of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, several Hungarian church leaders and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> announced major policy changes regarding religion. The party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said the party will not require that members be atheists and will not interfere in church affairs. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is not an atheist party but a party committed to the cause of social progress,'' <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Berecz </PERSON> said after the meeting in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. He told a news conference the party will ensure separation of church and state. There are no official statistics on church membership in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, but 70 percent of Hungarian Christians are believed to be Roman Catholics. In the past, some party members were known to be Catholics but they rarely professed their beliefs in public.
