<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill-Recovery     07-29 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Recovery,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Oil Spill Could Degrade in Five Years, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Valdez</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tidal action, erosion and oil-eating microbes could clean most of the oil from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s spill-tainted shores within five years and the beaches could be normal again in 10 years, researchers said Saturday. Speakers at a conference on the nation's largest oil spill said the natural combination could clean up the spill without human efforts. The tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> ran aground March 24 and spilled 10.92 million gallons of crude in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The researchers based their conclusions on studies of previous oil spills with similar characteristics, especially the <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION> spill off the coast of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1976. The researchers' findings contradicted statements by <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Vice Adm. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, the on-site coordinator of cleanup efforts. <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> said Friday that the beaches soiled by the spill `` are never going to be clean.'' `` I would be very surprised to see a significant amount of oil -LRB- in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> -RRB- in five years,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vandermeulen </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Halifax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>. He and <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON>, a microbiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION>, said studies of the <LOCATION> Cadiz </LOCATION> incident and other major spills showed that the ecology of the damaged areas appeared to have returned to normal within about 10 years. The researchers used comparisons of fouled areas with similar but unspoiled environments to determine what constituted `` normal.'' `` Most environments I have seen have had recovery to some level of normalcy within five to 10 years,'' <PERSON> Vandermeulen </PERSON> said. `` Even heavily oiled marshes have recovered in 11 years.'' The speed of natural cleanup by microbes is slowed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s cold temperatures, he said, but the breakdown of crude oil and weathering of shores by wind and erosion continues <PERSON> Atlas </PERSON> said oil-eating microbes exist in the area of the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> spill, in small numbers. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, which has a research station in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, has found that their numbers have increased since the spill, he said. Atlas also said general degradation of the <LOCATION> Cadiz </LOCATION> spill appeared to take around 10 years, even if nothing else was done. `` That rate is perhaps reasonable here,'' he said. Oil degradation can be sped up with the use of fertilizers containing nitrogen and phosphorus, a proposal that is being considered. Shore organisms that were destroyed by the spill would also come back fairly quickly, <PERSON> Vandermeusen </PERSON> said. `` Even if we wipe out every one, there are larval ones off shore waiting to settle,'' he said. The experts spoke before an estimated 150 researchers attending a three-day conference on the effects of the oil spill on people, animals and the environment. The conference, which ends Sunday, is sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Health and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, among others.
