<HEAD>Chinese Army Officer and Wife Defect to South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese army officer and his wife defected to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> Saturday through the demilitarized zone separating <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported. A government intelligence source, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified the officer as Maj. <PERSON> Zuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiukai </PERSON>, 40, a member of the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> delegation to the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armistice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The commission supervises the 1953 truce agreement that ended the Korean War. The source said <PERSON> Zuo </PERSON> and his wife requested that they be allowed to go to a third country. He said he did not know what country the couple preferred but speculated it would be either <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Obviously they do not want to settle down here,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Hankook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilbo </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentifed govenrment source as saying the couple probably defected because of their disapproval of the violent military crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators last month in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported they crossed the border into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> from the truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> inside the demilitarized zone shortly after 11 a.m. It said the two were under the protective custody of the American-led <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Yoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang-ro </PERSON> said command officials were questioning the officer and his wife and planned to transfer them to South Korean authorities. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> includes representatives of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 15 other nations that helped <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> after <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded in 1950. The command has headquarters in the border village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The government intelligence source said <PERSON> Zuo </PERSON> was the fourth-ranking officer in the 12-member Chinese delegation to the <ORGANIZATION> Armistice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, also based in <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>. Seoul-based foreign journalists who became acquainted with <PERSON> Zuo </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> said he speaks English and had served in the Chinese embassies in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> before being assigned to <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> two years ago. Assistant Foreign Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Jung-bin </PERSON> and other government officials met Saturday to discuss the case. The Taiwanese Embassy in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> said it was in contact with South Korean authorities. Some Chinese air force pilots who in past years defected and landed their jet fighters in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> were allowed to go to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, which is governed by the anti-communist Nationalist Chinese. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which sent thousands of troops into <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to help <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> during