<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 How do you make yourself at home in prison? Seventeen drug lords and their lieutenants used mahogany furniture, satin pillows, ornamental plants, porcelain figurines and a private sauna, the attorney general's office says. One even set up a cottage industry in his suite of cells in <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>, employing other inmates to make clothing for export, the office said. Photographs of <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ontiveros </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucero </PERSON>'s `` bedroom'' in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> newspapers Saturday showed a double bed with a thick cover and piles of pillows, elaborate mirrors and a wall-to-wall and floor-to-ceiling curtain. An investigation into prison corruption began with the disclosure earlier this month that two of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s biggest drug traffickers were living in opulent quarters in a <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> prison. While <PERSON> Ontiveros </PERSON> was branching out into haberdashery, other drug lords continued to run their narcotics businesses, using cellular telephones to call the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, the attorney general's office said. A total of 14 cellular telephones have been confiscated, the office said Friday when it released an inventory. The inventory listed microwave ovens, video cassette players, plants, refrigerators, an exercise bicycle, sauna baths, porcelain figurines, dining room furniture, bedroom furniture, office furniture and a jewel-encrusted Rolex watch. Tear gas, pistols, knives, scanners to monitor police radio traffic, cocaine and marijuana also were found, the statement said. The drug lords, men who go by nicknames like The <LOCATION> Beast </LOCATION> and The Quiet One, are now making do with the more Spartan surrounding of the high-security unit at the Southern Prison in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. They were transferred on July 21 from prisons in <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nuevo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION> in a special operation by federal agents. The attorney general's office also has begun an investigation into prison officials. It said the luxury in which the drug barons were allowed to live showed the degree of their `` economic power and the internal control based on terror.'' Earlier this month the director of prisons admitted that <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, accused of masterminding the 1985 torture-slaying of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, was living with his uncle and fellow drug lord in a space designed for 250 inmates. Walls had been knocked out to enlarge the cells, which were then outfitted with marble baths, a pool table, air conditioning, guest quarters and wardrobes crammed with dozens of silk shirts.
