<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MENOMINEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five farmers who died trying to save one another in a manure pit were buried Saturday as the family grappled with running the 100-year-old dairy. `` What forced them down into that pit? It certainly was n't fame or glory. It was love,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ade </PERSON> told more than 200 people who jammed the <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> for services for <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Theuerkauf </PERSON>, 65, his sons <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 37, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>, 28 and his grandson <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>, 15. `` It was true love for God, love for Christ, and love for a fellow man that caused what we termed a tragedy,'' Ade said. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Theuerkauf </PERSON> would have turned 66 today. The funeral for <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s cousin, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hofer </PERSON>, 63, was held later at <ORGANIZATION> Faith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in nearby <LOCATION> Marinette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis </LOCATION>. The five were overcome by methane fumes Wednesday morning trying to save each other at the Theuerkauf family dairy barn in <LOCATION> Menominee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Sheriff's officials believe <PERSON> Hofer </PERSON>, a farm employee, went into the 12-foot-deep pit first _ perhaps to clear a drain _ and collapsed after breathing the fumes, which are produced by manure. Each one followed to rescue the man before. <PERSON> Hofer </PERSON> was dead when deputies arrived, said <LOCATION> Menominee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff Deputy <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Corwin </PERSON>. Three others died later Wednesday morning at <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Area </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Marinette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and the fifth was pronounced dead at <LOCATION> Children </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Wauwatosa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, he said. There was about a foot of manure in the pit. County extension service director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Breyer </PERSON> said the entire community was shaken by the deaths. As a one-mile procession of mourners followed the hearses through town to a country cemetery, <LOCATION> Menominee </LOCATION> residents stood by their front windows and watched. Some stood outside in the rain and others pulled their cars off the road. The Theuerkauf farm has passed from father to son for more than 100 years. Now the only direct adult heir is <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s third son, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>, who was badly injured in an auto accident three years ago. <PERSON> Ade </PERSON> said the women will now run the farm. <PERSON> Breyer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON>, would meet with him Sunday to discuss how to handle the dairy farm, among the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>'s largest. The operation likely will have to be cut back. A memorial service was planned Sunday morning at the <LOCATION> Menominee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> fair, said fair manager <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Charlier </PERSON>. The county <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> closed down its fair booth this year so that volunteers who would have worked it could help the Theuerkaufs instead.
