<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 727 passenger jet lost its hydraulic system just before landing Saturday, forcing the pilot to manually lower the aircraft's landing gear, officials said. None of the 34 people aboard Flight 1042 from <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, was injured during the 4 p.m. landing at Greater <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, said a <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's deputy, who asked not to be identified. `` There was a loss of primary hydraulics,'' said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. A manual back-up system was used to lower the landing gear, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. The plane had to be towed down the runway once it landed. The airline had not determined why the hydraulic system malfunctioned. The jetliner would be grounded while the investigation continued, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. Passengers on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet said they first learned the jetliner was in difficulty when the pilot made an announcement minutes before it was supposed to land. `` He said we ca n't get the landing gear down,'' said <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wight </PERSON>, 52. `` Everyone said, ` Oh No!''' The jetliner, <PERSON> Wight </PERSON> said, circled <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> while the landing gear was put down manually. On July 19, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 crashed when a rear engine blew apart, causing complete hydraulic failure. The plane landed in a fiery somersault, killing 111 people. Elsewhere, two other minor airline incidents were reported on Saturday. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-9 lost its fiberglass tail cone while landing at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> but taxied to the gate without incident, an airline spokeswoman said. Flight 236 from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> landed at 10:10 a.m., carrying 99 passengers and a crew of six, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Bobbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> DC-8 with 197 passengers had to shut down one of its four engines before touching down Saturday night at <ORGANIZATION> Newark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, but landed safely, authorities said. There were no injuries reported in either incident.
