<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five congressmen on committees that oversee defense spending helped raise money for a pro-defense group from contractors who do business with the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, in its Sunday editions, reported seven major defense contractors contributed $ 100,000 each in tax deductible donations towards formation of the Institute for the <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> after four of the congressmen, one of them since deceased, invited them to a dinner in the fall of 1987. The congressmen included <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a longtime friend and former business partner to ICD's president, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markris </PERSON>, said the Post. Joining <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> in soliciting funds for the institute were: Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>; Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., who sits on the Appropriations defense subcommittee; and the late Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Chappell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., then chairman of the subcommittee, the newspaper <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Leath </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, invited the sponsoring firms to another fundraiser for the institute last May, according to the Post. But the contractors decided to end their support when they learned no new contributors had been brought into the venture since the first appeal in 1987. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leath </PERSON> also received speaking fees of $ 20,000 and $ 15,000 respectively from several of the same companies that helped established the group, the newspaper said. The institute's stated goal was to publicize the value of the defense industry. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> donated to the group because there `` was a definite feeling there was a need for this type of activity,'' company spokesman <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Spivak </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. `` It did n't hurt that it was supported by Congressman <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON>,'' he said. `` It probably helped.''
