<HEAD>Loan to White House Aide Investigated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special prosecutor is investigating whether an aide to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> violated federal ethics laws by failing to repay a $ 5,000 loan, a newspaper reported. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, is trying to determine whether a 1984 loan to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> was legitimate or if it represented an illegal gift or bribe from executives of a troubled <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> mortgage company, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions. <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON>, 37, runs the White House appointment office. The newspaper reported that the `` balloon'' - type loan from <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> was made in September 1984 for an original term of 90 days Under the arrangement, <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> did not have to pay interest, which amounted to 10 percent a year, or principal until the loan expired, and in December 1984, First American exercised an option clause that extended the loan for an additional year. The mortgage company sought protection under federal bankruptcy laws in late 1985, and its owner and other executives later were convicted on federal charges of defrauding company investors of millions of dollars. <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> tried on several occasions after the extension expired in December 1985 to repay the loan and its accumulated interest. But <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> `` just could n't get any information at all as to who owned the note,'' or where to send the money. The <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> said at least one former executive of the mortgage company has told investigators that an intermediary asked him to `` do him a favor and make this loan -LRB- to <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> -RRB- and that it was not to be paid back,'' presumably to win influence at the White House. The intermediary, an executive for a branch of a major Wall Street investment company, has denied making such a request, the newspaper's sources said. <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> never talked to the intermediary himself and was preparing to quit his job in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> White House and enter private law practice at the time he sought the loan. The newspaper said that a federal official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said evidence presented to a federal grand jury over the last six weeks `` appears to be supporting <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON>'s view that it is a legitimate loan. The official said the inquiry, which could last several more weeks, `` may very likely not lead to the indictment of anybody.'' `` It is my understanding that their probe has cleared -LRB- <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> -RRB- of any wrongdoing, and that they're going to close it out very shortly,'' <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cicconi </PERSON> declined through <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON> to be interviewed. <PERSON> Hundley </PERSON> said he now is negotiating repayment terms with a trustee of the company's assests appointed recently by the bankruptcy court.
