<HEAD>For release AMs Tuesday, August 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporate Dieting All Over Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like that friend of yours who regularly embarks on slim-and-trim diets, American industry is doing its thing again. It is seeking to slice poundage from its bureacracy, the better to court the consumer. Some of the biggest companies in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are doing it. Usually a company is measured large because of its sales and earnings. In this instance, some of the them are large also because of their bulging midriffs. Faced with competition that seems to grow more intense as foreigners invade each other's markets, companies are cutting much of their excess baggage _ plants, products and people. Almost all the big-name companies, the kind that seek to sell worldwide, are doing it. Not all of them are American companies either. The currency advantage that once gave Japanese firms an edge in exports is greatly reduced now, so they must become even more efficient. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> may become a vast common market in 1992, adding greatly to competitiveness there. But it's an old story in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. There was little industrial fat to be found in American companies right after World War II, but the easy days of the 1960s took care of that. Waste and inefficiency developed. By the 1970s, American companies were finding themselves at a competitive disadvantage. The industrial might of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, destroyed in the war, was much newer and more technologically efficient than American factories. The effect was shocking. The products of the bloated bureaucracies and dated factories of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> were undercut by foreign products shipped thousands of miles to showrooms. Foreign quality steadily improved while <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s fell. That shocking experience brought on a crash diet. Old factories were closed. Layers of white-collar workers were eliminated. Billions of dollars were spent on new production facilities. Nonessential units were sold off. That desperate diet of the 1970s had much to do with the success of American business in the 1980s. But success, it seems, has its dangers, the worst of them complacency. Bureaucratic baggage has accreted again. No company, no matter how great its reputation, is immune: Oldtimers such as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the Big Three automakers, post-war phenoms such as <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and upstart <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. After a terrible start, the decade of the 1980s has the appearance of the 1960s all over The economy has grown, unemployment has dropped and inflation and interest rates are under control again. And the fat has developed. Just 10 years after having been rescued from the edge of bankruptcy, and after having cut expenses to the bone, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is now forced to go on crash diet that, it hopes, will save $ 1 billion by the end of 1990. The proposed cuts reveal where the fat had grown: <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s white-collar work force, up about 50 percent in six years, would be reduced by 2,300 staffers Cost cuts in materials would be sought. Production would be streamlined. There is nothing new in such goals. In theory, such efficiencies are part of the unrelenting pursuit of good management. In practice, especially when times are comfortable, both theory and practice fall into disuse. What awakens both of them is competition, and competiton now is global rather than regional or national. The route to the consumer's heart is n't is nationality but price and quality. Only the slimmest and trimmest can offer it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for AMs Tuesday, July 01</NOTE>
