<HEAD>Bold Bid Reaches Dramatic Climax, But Story's Not Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The courts turned him down. Wall Street turned its back on him. So Paramount Chairman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> scrapped his $ 12.2 billion hostile offer for Time, vindicating the media giant's plan to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> But the story of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s seven-week-long struggle for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> did not end last week when <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> dropped his bid and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> completed its $ 14 billion tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The next chapters _ revealing what happens to these three sprawling entertainment-communications companies _ will unfold months and years from now. Time Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> is both optimistic and cautious about the future of the company that will be known as <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We've got nothing but healthy businesses,'' he said. `` We've acquired a company that's on an incredible roll. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>'s company also has taken on an estimated $ 13 billion in debt to complete the deal. That will crimp some of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s plans. `` This is going to make it a little tougher on us,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` We are going to probably not be as aggressive as we might be without that debt.'' Time's plans overseas _ which it hoped to expand through the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> deal _ could be limited because of the amount of money the company owes. `` Some of that will take capital we wo n't have,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said. `` Some things we would have liked to have done will take a little longer to get to.'' After Paramount launched its bid, some observers theorized <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> did not actually want to acquire Time _ and knew he'd fail _ but hoped to sabotage <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s competitive advantage. Regardless of <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' motivation, `` he did force Time to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> through debt rather than stock,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Anschel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It does limit <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s financial flexibility over the next year or two.'' Paramount's offer forced Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> to transform their planned stock-swap merger into a $ 70 a share tender offer by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. The only way Time could pay for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s 200 million shares was to borrow. But <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, who will co-run the company, evidently do n't expect debt to slow them down too much. `` You chew on the debt not by cutting creativity or firing people, but by growth,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said. First on <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s agenda is to decide the breakdown of cash and securities it will exchange for the 98 million <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shares not purchased in the cash tender offer _ what's known as the `` back end'' of the merger. The amount of cash involved and how much, if any, debt securities Time issues will help determine the size of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s debt load. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> expect to repay that debt through cash flow, an accounting term that refers to the money generated by their business. But while the companies stated in June that no asset sales were planned as a result of the merger, they sound less resolute now that they've got a done deal. Published reports have said Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> were considering selling Time's <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, <PERSON> Foresman </PERSON> book publisher and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s cable television operations. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said he could not imagine a sale of either business, but added, `` We really do n't know what we're going to do until we get the back end together and refine the cash flows.'' `` We would try very hard not to sell assets,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said. `` We'll know within six months.'' Some observers doubt whether <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> and <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>, two strong personalities, will be able to get along sharing the top job. `` That will be determined, but we know each other awful well,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said. Both executives negotiated the merger, resolving differences over two years of talks, and weathered <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s assault on their plans. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> claimed the pair `` survived that without one harsh word.'' <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> has served as a co-chief executive once before. He shared the top spot at <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON> from 1967 until <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON>'s death in 1971. `` We're putting together two companies that are so healthy, it makes it easier,'' <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said. `` The debt makes it a bit more difficult, but we really feel that's manageable.'' Analysts believe the debt will cushion <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZ