of suitor. During the seven weeks that Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> fought Paramount, the stock market was rife with rumors that bidders would emerge for any or all of the three combatants. Their stock prices gyrated as the reports came and went, but no bids were announced. Still, the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s bid is an interesting study of how Wall Street itself studies an offer. After Paramount announced its bid on June 6, the stock market bid Time shares up from $ 126 to a high of $ 182.75. But professional speculators and their own lawyers assessed <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s chances and saw that <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> would lose _ and began to dump their Time holdings. As the weeks wore on, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> stock spiraled downward, reaching about $ 136 as the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> heard the final arguments in the case.
