<HEAD>Bad Week For American Automakers and the UAW</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Autoworker unionists in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and automaker executives in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> are finding they have a lot in common: Both know what it's like to get their snouts snapped by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union suffered a stunning defeat this past week at the <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, where workers voted 2-to-1 to reject <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> representation despite an intensive and often bitter union campaign that began in January 1988. Not only did the rejection signal a repudiation of the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Union Yes'' drive at the 6-year-old plant, but it also was seen as a sign that American workers are increasingly accepting Japanese management techniques <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION> workers, who produce light trucks and Sentra sedans, make the same money as <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> counterparts elsewhere and none has ever been laid off, making it difficult for the union to find an effective campaign issue. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> blamed the defeat on what it called <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s systematic anti-union rhetoric. The vote was big news in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where companies that rely heavily on sales in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, particularly automakers, have been building more factories in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, both to thwart charges of trade protectionism and to gain a stronger presence in this country. So far, no transplanted Japanese auto factory has been organized by the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>, and the <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION> vote intensified speculation that the country's largest union will face more trouble plugging the holes in its declining membership. The union was n't the only one smarting from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s influence on the automaking industry. Five hundred miles north of <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, two of the Big Three reported lower second-quarter earnings because of declining domestic sales, and a third announced a $ 1 billion cost-cutting effort, partly the result of aggressive Japanese competition. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said earnings fell 3 percent from a year earlier to $ 1.45 billion, and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said earnings fell 15 percent to $ 1.4 billion. Industry analysts said the rebates offered by the carmakers not only failed to lure enough buyers but eroded whatever earnings were left. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> which is to report earnings Monday, confronted perhaps a more serious problem of growing costs, evoking memories of gloomy days several years ago when the company needed federal loan guarantees to stay alive. The No. 3 automaker's chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, widely credited with resurrecting <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, told top managers the company was too fat and they needed to cut 2,300 white-collar workers from the payroll by yearend. A slump in the auto business has been expected for a while, and many industry analysts foresee drastically lower earnings at the Big Three over the remainder of 1989 and perhaps 1990. The automakers themselves have indicated they agree with that assessment. In one telling sign this past week, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s profitable financial services business for $ 3.35 billion cash. The purchase was seen as part of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to protect itself from dependence on selling cars to make money. Elsewhere in business and economic news this past week: _ Bigger evidently is better in the drug business <ORGANIZATION> Bristol-Myers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Squibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to merge in a stock swap valued at about $ 11 billion, creating one of the largest pharmaceutical companies. The agreement came a day after <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beckman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Beecham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> completed their previously announced merger. _ <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> completed its merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> after <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>'s highest court blocked Paramount Communication's hostile takeover attempt of The court's decision was seen as a major victory for corporate directors whose long-term plans may conflict with the wishes of shareholders. _ More evidence of a slowing economy emerged, boosting stock and bond prices The government said its broadest measure of economic growth showed a 1.7 percent gain this spring, well below expectations. Economists said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, which has taken steps to ease credit, would likely continue to do so in order to avert a possible recession. _ <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said the cost of cleaning the Alaskan oil spill would exceed $ 1.25 billion and was responsible for a plunge in its second-quarter earnings The disclosure coincided with a five-month low in the price of oil, which had been driven higher by fears of shortages that followed the March 24 spill.
