<HEAD>Wall Street Shuns Stocks Likely to be Jarred as Economy Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf ``This analysis ...'' to UPDATE with Friday records.
Picks up 6th graf ``For all of the week ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a long time circling the runway on dwindling power, the once high-flying economy finally may be touching down. Stock market investors have braced for a possibly difficult landing by favoring companies that can turn a profit regardless of economic conditions and dumping ones apt to be bumped around during impact. The economy probably started on its final approach to the runway during the second quarter when growth eased considerably to a 1.7 percent annual pace. Many analysts regarded the report issued this past week on the gross national product _ the broadest gauge of economic activity _ as a signal that the economy has sufficient power for the sought-after `` soft landing,'' a period of slow but sustained growth with falling inflation and interest rates. This analysis helped various stock market measures scale to record heights during the week. On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index climbed to 342.15 and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index advanced to 190.38, both all-time highs For all of the week, the market made some impressive progress. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished the week at 2,635.24, just 0.19 point below the post-crash high reached Thursday, up 27.88 points for the week and just about 87 points shy of its all time high of 2,722.42 set in August 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> composite index rose 3.23 to 190.38; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market added 3.53 to 452.82; and, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> market value index was up 3.23 at 374.51. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> averaged 179.62 million shares a day, up slightly from 175.90 million a day the previous week. One force driving the market onward was evidence that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> was fluffing the credit cushion to make the economy's landing more comfortable. The central bank took steps this past week to loosen short-term interest rates. Declining interest rates bode well for the stock and bond markets, says <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Hundreds of billions of dollars now invested in money market funds in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could go elsewhere if rates continue to fall. `` Any further drops in short-term interest rates as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> shifts policy for recession prevention could also unleash a fairly powerful flow of money into longer-term financial assets such as stocks and bonds,'' he wrote in a weekly market strategy report. A look at recent Wall Street trends indicates investors have been discriminating in their selections. Stocks of companies with earnings swings during business cycles, such as automakers, have performed weakly for some time while more recession-proof companies, such as foodmakers and consumer product companies, have fared better. `` The market is really penalizing those companies that will be bothered by a recession,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> says he sees two chief reasons why a sluggish economic growth wo n't deteriorate into a serious downturn, with widespread layoffs and significant income shrinkage. Most importantly, he says, the central bank has ample leeway to lower interest rates without stirring up inflation. `` There's no reason why the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has to stay tight,'' says <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>. `` In prior recessions, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> felt it could n't loosen because it's job on inflation was n't working.'' The second safeguard is that consumers already have made major progress in replenishing their savings depleted during the longest economic expansion in the post-World War II era, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> contends. A government report released Friday showed the personal savings rate _ savings as a percent of disposable income _ rose to 5.9 percent in June, well above the sub-3-percent rates that prevailed a few years ago. `` Part of the function of a recession is to reliquify the consumer,'' says <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>. `` The consumer is already partially reliquified.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End of Adv for Weekend Editions July 29-30</NOTE>
